GEOLOGIC SETTING, FAUNA, AND AGE. — Extensive exposures of middle to late Cenozoic sediments in northern Junggar Basin and its western extension in Kazakhstan produce a rich record of fossil vertebrates ( Fig. 1 ). Explorations of the Junggar Basin by Chinese geologists began in the 1950s. Although Chow (1957 , 1958 ) was first to report fragmentary mammal fossils from several Cenozoic localities in Xinjiang, all collected by local geological survey and petroleum teams, dedicated explorations by vertebrate paleontologists did not begin until 1982 and 1984 , when a joint IVPP and Xinjiang Bureau of Petroleum team worked in the Ulungu River region. A basic stratigraphic framework of the Suosuoquan Formation and Halamagai Formation, plus associated vertebrate fossils, was first established by
Tong et al. (1990)
. Since then various efforts have focused on the regional stratigraphy and chronology (
